    <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
        <body>
            <div xml:id="KT392-kilavi">
                <p type="edition">varaiviṭaik kiḻattiyatu nilaimai tumpikkac colluvāḷāycb
                    ciṟaippuṟamākat tōḻi colliyatu. </p>


                <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">Uttered by the confidante, while [he] is behind
                    the hedge, as if talking to a bee about HER state [when awaiting] the time of
                    marriage. </p>
            </div>

            <div xml:id="KT392">
                <lg type="edition">
                    <l> amma vāḻiyō vaṇicciṟait tumpi</l>
                    <l> naṉmoḻik kacca millai yavarnāṭ</l>
                    <l> ṭaṇṇa ṉeṭuvaraic cēṟi yāyiṟ</l>
                    <l> kaṭavai miṭainta tuṭavaiyañ ciṟutiṉait</l>
                    <l> tuḷareṟi nuṇṭukaṭ kaḷaiñar taṅkai</l>
                    <l> tamariṟ ṟīrā ḷeṉmō varacar</l>
                    <l> niraicela ṉuṇṭōl pōlap</l>
                    <l> piracan tūṅku malaikiḻa vōrkkē.</l>


                </lg>

                <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                    <l> Alas, may you live, bee with adorning wings,</l>
                    <l> fear [to utter] good words is not [necessary]. <note place="foot">The end of
                        the <term xml:lang="ta">illai </term> sentence is not marked in any way. An
                        alternative way of construing would be to take <term xml:lang="ta">illai </term>
                        as a 2nd sg. and an address: "you who have no fear of good words".</note>
                    </l>
                    <l rend="indent"> If you go to the majestic long mountain of his land,</l>
                    <l> say to the master of the mountain, where honeycombs are hanging</l>
                    <l rend="indent2"> like fine shields, going in a row for the king:</l>
                    <l> “she<choice>
                            <seg> won't end </seg>
                            <seg>has not ceased [to live] </seg>
                        </choice>with
                        her people,</l>
                    <l> the younger sister of the pickers in the fine dust,</l>
                    <l rend="indent8"> where they hack weeds <note place="foot">How to understand
                        the subtle syntax and meaning of line 5? According to T.V.G. the people have
                        little pickaxes to remove the weed from the millet fields, and these tools
                        are named <term xml:lang="ta">tuḷar</term>. This is not attested by the DEDR
                        (the word is simply missing); the TL knows only the meaning "weed", but
                        several parallels seem to refer to the same situation (AN 184.13; see Nacc.
                        on Malaipaṭuk. 123, Nacc. on Perumpāṇ. 201).</note>
                    </l>
                    <l rend="indent3"> from the little millet by the wood <note place="foot">What is
                        here the function of <term xml:lang="ta">tuṭavai-y-am</term> ? Is the millet
                        meant to be planted close to the wood and thus quasi belongs to it?</note>
                        crowded with trespassers.”</l>

                    <lg type="alternate" sameAs="6b">
                        <l>“she has not ceased [to live] with her people”, <note place="foot">While
                            the first rendering would contain a reassurance (SHE will not stay with
                            her family forever, i.e. you have a chance of getting her), the second
                            seems to be a complaint, which is in accordance with the <term xml:lang="ta">kiḷavi</term> : you still have not married her.</note>
                        </l>
                    </lg>
                </lg>
            </div>
